03867nam a2200529Ia 9781478027904DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20242024ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814780279047 a10.1515/97814780279042doi  a(DE-B1597)689951  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aB3305 7aPHI0190002bisacsh1 aDussel, Enrique, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Theological Metaphors of Marx /cEnrique Dussel. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2024] 4c©2024  a1 online resource (248 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tTranslator’s Note -- tForeword: On Karl Marx’s Negative Meta-Theology -- tPreliminary Words -- tPrologue to the English-Language Edition: The Criticism of Theology as the Criticism of Economics -- tPart I: The Critique of Fetishism -- tIntroduction -- t1: Fetishism in the Young Marx, 1835–1857 -- t2: Fetishism in the Four Versions of Capital, 1857–1882 -- t3: A Critique of Capital’s Fetishistic Character -- tPart II: Theological “Metaphors” -- tIntroduction -- t4: Marx’s “Metaphorical” Theology -- t5: The Cultic Sacrifice of the Fetish: The Use of Biblical Texts -- t6: Marx’s Atheism and That of the Prophets of Israel -- tAppendix: The Epistemological Decolonization of Theology -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn The Theological Metaphors of Marx, Enrique Dussel provides a groundbreaking combination of Marxology, theology, and ethical theory. Dussel shows that Marx unveils the theology of capitalism in his critique of commodity fetishization. Capitalism constitutes an idolatry of the commodity that undergirds the capitalist expropriation of labor. Dussel examines Marx’s early writings on religion and fetishism and proceeds through what Dussel refers to as the four major drafts of Capital, ultimately situating Marx’s philosophical, economic, ethical, and historical insights in relation to the theological problems of his time. Dussel notes a shift in Marx’s underlying theological schema from a political critique of the state to an economic critique of the commodity fetish as the Devil, or anti-God, of modernity. Marx’s thought, impact, and influence cannot be fully understood without Dussel’s historic reinterpretation of the theological origins and implications of Marx’s critiques of political economy and politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aFetishism2DLC. 0aMetaphorxReligious aspects2DLC. 0aPhilosophy2DLC. 0aTheology2DLC. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh1 aDussel, Enrique, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMendieta, Eduardo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPérez-Bustillo, Camilo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478027904?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478027904423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478027904/original  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles